06562nam a22011295i 9780813558325DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20032003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135583257 a10.36019/97808135583252doi  a(DE-B1597)529861  a(OCoLC)1164097931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHQ767.9b.R46 2004eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.2322200aRethinking Childhood /ced. by Peter B. Pufall, Richard P. Unsworth. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series in Childhood Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeing a child in American society can be problematic. Twenty percent of American children live in poverty, parents are divorcing at high rates, and educational institutions are not always fulfilling their goals. Against this backdrop, children are often patronized or idealized by adults. Rarely do we look for the strengths within children that can serve as the foundation for growth and development. In Rethinking Childhood, twenty contributors, coming from the disciplines of anthropology, government, law, psychology, education, religion, philosophy, and sociology, provide a multidisciplinary view of childhood by listening and understanding the ways children shape their own futures. Topics include education, poverty, family life, divorce, neighborhood life, sports, the internet, and legal status. In all these areas, children have both voice and agency. They construct their own social networks and social reality, sort out their own values, and assess and cope with the perplexing world around them. The contributors present ideas that lead not only to new analyses but also to innovative policy applications. Taken together, these essays develop a new paradigm for understanding childhood as children experience these years. This paradigm challenges readers to develop fresh ways of listening to children’s voices that enable both children and adults to cross the barriers of age, experience, and stereotyping that make communication difficult. A volume in the Rutgers Series in Childhood Studies, edited by Myra Bluebond-Langner.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChildrenxSocial conditions. 0aChildren. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAird, Enola G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAird, Enola.1 aAllen, Brenda A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Brenda.1 aBennett Woodhouse, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoykin, A. Wade, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoykin, A. Wade.1 aCassell, Justine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassell, Justine.1 aDucharme, Raymond A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDucharme, Raymond.1 aEmery, Robert E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmery, Robert.1 aEtheredge, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtheredge, Susan.1 aGray, Karen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Karen.1 aHearst, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHearst, Alice.1 aJames, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Allison.1 aKorbin, Jill E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorbin, Jill.1 aLindner, Eileen W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindner, Eileen.1 aMatthews, Gareth B., econtributor.4ctb4https